flowRoot.flowPara: Context menu, buttons, favicon for extension pages and info bar
Select the desired gradient, Ctrl-C, then select the backgrounds and paste the style with Ctrl-Shift-V. Use the gradient tool to fit the gradient to the shapes.
You can, of course, make your own gradient. These are just meant to help you getting started.

Hit # to turn the grid on/off. Objects will snap to pixels when it's on. This produces sharper icons when exporting to raster images. Inkscape performance might be bad doing this, so typing exact coordinates might be an alternative.

Open the 'Layers' dialog (Ctrl-Shift-L) and drag its window bottom edge down to reveal all the layers. Select the 'user icons' layer and paste/create your icon vector shape into it. Hide the 'example icons' layer by clicking on the eye icon in the layer dialog.
Duplicate your icon shape (Ctrl-D) so you have four and move them to the icon background shapes. Scale them to about 85% of full size (in parenthesis) and tweak for sharpness.

There's an 'Icon Preview' on the 'View' menu that can help you previewing raster image output of the vector shapes, but to get the default sizes of Opera extension icons, you'll have to edit the preferences.xml of Inkscape.
This template has predefined slice shapes that must be perfectly aligned with the background shapes. Be careful not to move either of these.
Copy a color gradient from the palette and paste it to the background shapes. Or make one yourself. Please try to be somewhat conservative in color choices.
To export icons, click the eye icon of the 'slices' layer to make it visible. Click on the icon you want to export and hit 'Export Bitmap ..." (Ctrl-Shift-E). Repeat for all the four icons.
